  "prompt": "How do you find the magnitude of the a net force using a formula?",
  "response": "To find the magnitude of the net force, you can use the following methods:\n\n1. Pythagorean Theorem Method (for perpendicular forces):\nF_net = \u221a(F1\u00b2 + F2\u00b2)\n- Where F1 and F2 are perpendicular forces\n- Used when forces are at right angles to each other\n\n2. Vector Addition Method:\nF_net = \u221a[(Fx)\u00b2 + (Fy)\u00b2]\n- Fx = sum of x-component forces\n- Fy = sum of y-component forces\n- Used for forces at different angles\n\n3. General Vector Addition:\nF_net = \u221a(\u03a3Fx)\u00b2 + (\u03a3Fy)\u00b2)\n- \u03a3Fx = total of all x-component forces\n- \u03a3Fy = total of all y-component forces\n- Useful for multiple forces acting in different directions\n\nKey steps:\n1. Resolve forces into x and y components\n2. Sum the components\n3. Use Pythagorean theorem to calculate magnitude\n4. Square root the sum of squared components\n\nThe specific method depends on the force configuration and given information.",
